d"},"nl":{"1250–":"1250–Overleden","1250–Male":"1250–Overleden","1252–Female":"1252–Overleden","1268–Male":"1268–Overleden","1276–Male":"1276–Overleden","1285–1335":"1285–1335","1226–1272":"1226–1272","1285":"1285","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1335":"1335","1268":"1268","ABT 1276":"circa 1276","1276":"1276","about 1268":"circa 1268","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Exbourne, Devon, England":"Exbourne, Devon, England","Giddecote, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"1250–":"1250–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1252–Female":"1252–Deceased","1268–Male":"1268–Deceased","1276–Male":"1276–Deceased","1285–1335":"1285–1335","1226–1272":"1226–1272","1285":"1285","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1335":"1335","1268":"1268","ABT 1276":"about 1276","1276":"1276","about 1268":"about 1268","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Exbourne, Devon, England":"Exbourne, Devon, England","Giddecote, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dennis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Denis(e)</i>, <i>Dinis(e)</i>, vernacular forms of Latin <i>Dionysius</i>, Greek <i>Dionysios</i> ‘(follower) of <i>Dionysos</i>’, an eastern god introduced to the classical pantheon at a relatively late date and bearing a name of probably Semitic origin. The name was borne by various early Christian saints, including Saint Denis, the martyred 3rd-century bishop of Paris who became the patron saint of France. From the 12th century onward, the popularity of the name in England (and of its cognates, mainly   Denis  , in the continental Europe) seems to have been largely due to French influence. The feminine form <i>Dionysia</i> (in vernacular English likewise <i>Den(n)is</i>) is also found, and some examples of the surname may originate from it.","English: from Middle English <i>deneis</i>, a variant of <i>danais</i> ‘Danish’, with the vowel influenced by Middle English <i>denshe</i> (Old English <i>denisc</i>). Compare   Dence  .","Irish (mainly Dublin and Cork): of the same origin as 1 and 2 above, sometimes an alternative form to   Donohue   but more often to   McDonough  , since the personal name <i>Donnchadh</i> was Anglicized as <i>Donough</i> or <i>Denis</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Dec","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Aleksander, Andrzej, Casimir, Ignacy, Jerzy, Krystyna, Krzysztof, Malgorzata, Mikolaj, Stanislaw, Tadeusz.","Polish: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Dionizy</i>, Polish form of <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  )."]},{"name":"Dennison","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name <i>Denis</i> (see   Dennis  ) + <i>-son</i>. Compare   Tennyson  .","English (of Norman origin): from Anglo-Norman French <i>deinzein</i>, a burgess who enjoyed the privileges of those living <i>deinz la cité</i> ‘within the city’."]},{"name":"Denny","meanings":["English and Scottish: from Middle English <i>Den(n)y</i>, a pet form of the personal name <i>Denis</i> (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Tenney  .","English: habitational name from Danny in Hurstpierpoint, Sussex, recorded as <i>Danye</i> in 1343. Alternatively, the name may arise from Denny in Waterbeach, Cambridgeshire, but no medieval evidence with a habitative preposition has been found in the case of the latter.","Scottish: habitational name from Denny in Stirlingshire."]},{"name":"Diniz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Augusto, Celso, Francisco, Luis, Ricardo, Rogerio, Alvaro, Anselmo, Antero, Carlos.  Portuguese Joao, Marcio.","Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Dinis</i>, a vernacular form of <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  )."]},{"name":"Denes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Bela, Laszlo, Miklos, Tibor, Aranka, Balint, Endre, Ferenc, Lajos, Zoltan.  Jewish Imrich, Meyer.  Romanian Doina, Matei, Radu.","Hungarian (<b>Dénes</b>): from the personal name <i>Dénes</i>, from Greek <i>Dionysios</i> (see   Dennis  ). The surname <i>Dénes</i> is also found in Slovakia; compare 2 below.","Slovak (<b>Deneš</b> and <b>Déneš</b>) and Romanian (also <b>Deneş</b>): from the Hungarian personal name <i>Dénes</i> ‘Dennis’, or an adaptation of the Hungarian surname <b>Dénes</b> (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Dennett","meanings":["English: from a pet form of Middle English <i>Denis</i> (see   Dennis  ), or possibly from a pet form of <i>Denise</i>, as, for example, <i>Denote</i>, a female character in <i>Piers Plowman</i>."]},{"name":"Dinges","meanings":["German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dings  ."]},{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Dings","meanings":["Dutch and German: from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Dionysius</i> (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dinges  ."]},{"name":"Dinis","meanings":["Portuguese and Galician: from <i>Dinis</i>, a Portuguese personal name equivalent to   Dennis  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":65,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":78,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Dennis was born in 1250, in Devon, England as the son of Alan Dennis. He married Maud Manworthey in 1273, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1250–":"1250–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1252–Female":"1252–Surnud","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1276–Male":"1276–Surnud","1285–1335":"1285–1335","1226–1272":"1226–1272","1285":"1285","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1335":"1335","1268":"1268","ABT 1276":"umbes 1276","1276":"1276","about 1268":"umbes 1268","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Exbourne, Devon, England":"Exbourne, Devon, England","Giddecote, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1250–":"1250–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1252–Female":"1252–Kuollut","1268–Male":"1268–Kuollut","1276–Male":"1276–Kuollut","1285–1335":"1285–1335","1226–1272":"1226–1272","1285":"1285","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1335":"1335","1268":"1268","ABT 1276":"noin 1276","1276":"1276","about 1268":"noin 1268","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Exbourne, Devon, England":"Exbourne, Devon, England","Giddecote, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devonshire, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"1250–":"1250–Décédé","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","1252–Female":"1252–Décédée